10.body: By the end of this lab, students will be able to: Successfully install the R programming language. Install the RStudio Desktop Integrated Development Environment (IDE). Verify the installation by running a simple command.
10.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Learning Objectives
10.title: Learning Objectives

11.body: To perform data science at DCC, we use two primary tools. Think of R as the "engine" of a car and RStudio as the "dashboard." You need the engine to go, but you need the dashboard to steer and see where you are going. If you are using a DCC Chromebook or a computer where you cannot install software, please contact the instructor about using **Posit Cloud** (the web-based version of RStudio).
11.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Introduction
11.title: Introduction

12.body: You must install R before you install RStudio. Go to the CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network) website. Select the download link for your operating system: Download R for Windows -> Click "base" -> Click "Download R 4.x.x for Windows." Download R for (macOS) -> Download the .pkg file that matches your chip (Apple silicon M1/M2 or Intel). Run the downloaded installer and keep all default settings by clicking "Next" or "Continue."
12.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Step 1: Install R (The Engine)
12.title: Step 1: Install R (The Engine)

13.body: RStudio is the interface where you will write your code and view your data visualizations. Visit the Posit Download Page . Scroll down to "2: Install RStudio" and click the button for your operating system. Run the installer. Like R, it is best to keep all default settings.
13.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Step 2: Install RStudio (The Dashboard)
13.title: Step 2: Install RStudio (The Dashboard)

14.body: Let's make sure the "engine" and "dashboard" are talking to each other. Open RStudio from your applications folder or start menu. Find the Console pane (usually on the bottom left). Type the following code and press Enter : print("Hello, MAT 186!")
14.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Step 3: Verify Your Setup
14.title: Step 3: Verify Your Setup

15.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto Documents
15.title: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto Documents

16.body: Create an RStudio Project to organize your work. Understand the structure of a Quarto (.qmd) document. "Render" a document into a professional HTML report.
16.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Learning Objectives
16.title: Learning Objectives

17.body: In Data Science, organization is everything. An RStudio Project keeps your code, data, and images in one "folder" so R always knows where to look. Open RStudio. Click File > New Project... Select New Directory > New Project . Name your directory MAT186_Labs and save it to your Desktop or Documents. **Why use Projects?** It sets the "Working Directory" automatically. You'll never have to type long file paths like `C:/Users/Documents/Data...` again!
17.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 1: RStudio Projects
17.title: Part 1: RStudio Projects

18.body: Quarto allows you to combine text, code, and results in one file. Click File > New File > Quarto Document... Title it "Lab 2" and put your name as the Author. Click Create . Look at the file. You will see: YAML Header: The stuff between the --- lines (Title, Author, Format). Code Chunks: The gray boxes starting with ```{r}. Markdown: The plain white areas for your written analysis.
18.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 2: Creating a Quarto Document
18.title: Part 2: Creating a Quarto Document

19.body: To turn your code into a report: Click the Render button (blue arrow icon) at the top of the editor. RStudio will save the file and pop up a beautiful HTML window. **Lab Task 2:** Inside your Quarto document, create a new code chunk and type `2 + 2`. Render the document and verify that the number `4` appears in the final report. Screenshot your rendered HTML for submission.
19.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 3: Rendering (The "Magic" Button)
19.title: Part 3: Rendering (The "Magic" Button)

20.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto
20.title: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto

21.body: Distinguish between Inline and Display math modes in Quarto. Use LaTeX syntax to write essential statistical symbols ($\mu, \sigma, \bar{x}$). Format complex equations like Linear Regression for professional lab reports.
21.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Learning Objectives
21.title: Learning Objectives

22.body: In Data Science, we often need to document the mathematical models we use. Quarto uses a system called LaTeX (pronounced "Lay-tek") to render math. This ensures your formulas look professional and are accessible to screen readers.
22.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Introduction
22.title: Introduction

23.body: There are two ways to display math in your Quarto documents depending on where you want the formula to appear.
23.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Part 1: The Two Math Modes
23.title: Part 1: The Two Math Modes

24.body: Use a single dollar sign $ ... $ when the math should stay inside a sentence. Code: The population mean is represented by $\mu$. Result: The population mean is represented by $\mu$.
24.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » 1. Inline Math
24.title: 1. Inline Math

25.body: Use double dollar signs $$...$$ to put the formula on its own line, centered. Code: $$\bar{x} = \frac{\sum x_i}{n}$$ Result: $$\bar{x} = \frac{\sum x_i}{n}$$
25.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » 2. Display Math
25.title: 2. Display Math

26.body: Copy and paste these codes into your Quarto document to practice: Statistical Term LaTeX Code Rendered Result Sample Mean $\bar{x}$ $\bar{x}$ Standard Deviation $\sigma$ $\sigma$ Summation $\sum$ $\sum$ Correlation Coefficient $r$ $r$ Coefficient of Determination $R^2$ $R^2$
26.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Part 2: Common Symbols for MAT 186
26.title: Part 2: Common Symbols for MAT 186

27.body:
For Linear Regression, we combine several symbols. Try typing this in your Quarto file: Code: $$y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon$$ Result: $$y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon$$ **Lab Task 3:** 1. Open your `MAT186_Labs` project in RStudio.
2. Create a new Quarto document (`.qmd`) titled "Math Practice."
3. Write the formula for the **Standard Deviation** exactly as shown below: `$$s = \sqrt{\frac{\sum (x_i - \bar{x})^2}{n - 1}}$$`
4. **Render** the document to HTML and confirm the formula appears correctly.
27.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Part 3: Writing Equations
27.title: Part 3: Writing Equations

28.body: Spaces: Do not put a space between the $ and your math code. Bad: $ \mu $ Good: $\mu$ Missing Signs: If your formula looks like plain text, check if you forgot the closing $.
28.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Troubleshooting Math Errors
28.title: Troubleshooting Math Errors

29.body: When you use this LaTeX method, students using screen readers can hear the math described clearly (e.g., "x bar equals fraction sum x sub i over n"). This is much better than using an image of an equation, which a screen reader cannot "see."
29.breadcrumbs: Lab 3: Mathematical Notation in Quarto » Accessibility Check
29.title: Accessibility Check

3.body: CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network): The global network of servers that stores and distributes R and its packages. Think of it as the "App Store" for R.

30.title: Lab 4: Creating Your Data Science Portfolio on GitHub

31.body: Create a personal GitHub account. Initialize a new repository for MAT 186 work. Understand the "Commit" and "Push" workflow. Host a live version of a lab report using GitHub Pages.
31.title: Learning Objectives

32.body: Data Science is a collaborative field. GitHub is the industry standard for version control and sharing code. In this lab, you will set up your own "portfolio"—a place where you can showcase the work you do in this class to future employers or transfer institutions.
32.title: Introduction

33.body: Go to GitHub.com . Sign up for a free account. Tip: Choose a professional username (e.g., jsmith-dcc), as you may show this to employers later! Verify your email address.
33.breadcrumbs: Lab 4: GitHub Repository » Part 1: Setting Up Your Account
33.title: Part 1: Setting Up Your Account

34.body: A Repository (or "Repo") is like a project folder that lives in the cloud. Click the + icon in the top right and select New repository . Repository name: mat186-work Description: "Labs and projects for Introduction to Data Science at DCC." Public/Private: Select Public . Check the box that says Add a README file . Click Create repository .
34.breadcrumbs: Lab 4: GitHub Repository » Part 2: Creating Your First Repository
34.title: Part 2: Creating Your First Repository

35.body: Now, let's add the work you've done in previous labs. In your new mat186-work repository, click Add file > Upload files . Drag and drop your HTML files from Lab 2 and Lab 3 into the browser. At the bottom, type a "Commit message" like: Initial upload of Lab 2 and 3. Click Commit changes .
35.breadcrumbs: Lab 4: GitHub Repository » Part 3: Uploading Your Lab Reports
35.title: Part 3: Uploading Your Lab Reports

36.body:
Let's make your lab reports viewable as actual websites. Go to your repository Settings tab. On the left menu, click Pages . Under Build and deployment , set the Branch to main and click Save . After a minute, GitHub will give you a URL (e.g., https://username.github.io/mat186-work/). **Lab Task 4:** 1. Create your `mat186-work` repository.
2. Upload the HTML version of your Lab 3 (Math Formulas).
3. Enable GitHub Pages.
4. Paste the link to your live GitHub Page into the Brightspace assignment.
36.breadcrumbs: Lab 4: GitHub Repository » Part 4: Publishing with GitHub Pages
36.title: Part 4: Publishing with GitHub Pages

37.body: By putting your work on GitHub, you are participating in Open Science . This allows others to learn from your code and allows you to track your own progress throughout the semester!
37.breadcrumbs: Lab 4: GitHub Repository » A Note on Open Science
37.title: A Note on Open Science

5.body: IDE (Integrated Development Environment): A software application (like RStudio) that provides comprehensive facilities to computer programmers for software development.
5.title: I

6.body: Markdown: A lightweight markup language with plain-text-formatting syntax. It allows you to write formatted text that can be easily converted to HTML.
6.title: M

7.body: Quarto: The next-generation version of RMarkdown. It is an open-source scientific and technical publishing system used to create documents, books, and websites.
7.title: Q

8.body: YAML: Stands for "Yet Another Markup Language." In Quarto, the YAML header (at the top of the file) is where you define settings like the title, author, and output format.
